<br>
In your readings did it seem that Western Europe is just taking a breather from construction, or are they actively -by law-  reversing their previous nuclear acceptance - up to and including dismantling running reactors?<br>
<br>
yale<br>
<br>
If you decide to take a pass, I will supply a country by country survey. The problem is that my words and references seem to hold no credibility for Wayne.<br>
<br>
BTW - Zaphod.. I tracked that reference in Platts to a &quot;planned reactor&quot;. It is a controversial proposal to build, not a generating plant, but a test prototype of an experimental PWR.  Its pretty iffy if it gets funded. <br>
======================================<br>
<br>
BTW - PO...<br>
&quot;A handful of them are all that's required to meet all of France's energy needs.&quot;<br>
I don't follow that statement. They have built -54- reactors! It still only provides 3.9 quads of energy out of France's 10.3 quad energy demand. Most of France's energy requirements cannot be met by nuclear electrification, thus the plan by France to let capacity slip.<br>
You comment about breeders makes no sense. France has bailed on breeders and switched off both Phenix and SuperPhenix. No one in the western world are doing breeders. They don't make the slightest economic sense.<br>
