<br>
Breeders were abandoned (in addition to technical failure and proliferation issues) because they CANNOT COMPETE ECONOMICALLY.<br>
<br>
The assumption in the past was that uranium was in short supply. Re-read your reference. That 1983 reference by Cohen was based on supplies lasting only a few tens of years (the lifetime of EXISTING plants)<br>
<br>
That has proven to be not the case:<br>
-------------------------------------------------<br>
US reactors use roughly a total of 52 miilion pounds of U3O8 per year.<br>
<br>
USA Uranium available at $50 per pound or less:<br>
<br>
US reserves = ~1175 million pounds (about a 22 year supply)<br>
US Estimated Additional Resources = ~ 5000 million pounds (about 100 year supply)<br>
US Speculative Resources = ~3500 million pounds (about a 67 year supply)<br>
<br>
Total US low cost Uranium = ~190 year supply<br>
----------------------------------------------<br>
In addition, there is a vast stockpile of HEU and Pu from the weapons programs (It is glutting an already collapsed uranium market)<br>
---------------------------------<br>
<br>
What about when all this runs out?<br>
Once-thru reactors only use about 1/2 of the actinide fuel.<br>
Reprocessing the fuel multiplies your available fuel stocks.<br>
(Reprocessing is required for breeders, so it is an expense that must be added anyway)<br>
-----------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Thus without ANY incredibly expensive (and nasty) breeders, US reactors have between 150 and 300 years or so of fuel.<br>
<br>
That is just USA stocks. World uranium resources (australia, africa, etc) dwarf US stocks.<br>
<br>
Hence, as I said, all Western nations have bailed on breeders.<br>
<br>
yale<br>
