<br>
The &quot;nasty&quot; is my NVHO. I am considering these typical aspects of a FBR (different designs have differing characteristics, each with specific advantages and disadvantages).<br>
<br>
1) The use of molten sodium.<br>
Big complication in operations. Molten sodium is opaque requiring complex tools to manage and observe operations.<br>
It is violently reactive. Just touching concrete can set it off.<br>
<br>
2) Potential for a very low-level nuclear explosion. Due to the enrichment and operating characteristics, a &quot;rapid energetic disassembly event&quot; (love that phrase!) is possible. Demolition of the reactor is a distinct possibility.<br>
<br>
3) Speed of accident. Due to the characteristics of FBRs, core damage can happen in a flash, before intervention can occur.<br>
<br>
4) requires reprocessing facilities (either local or off-site).<br>
No one involved with the reprocessing business thinks its anything beyond a necessary evil. It is dirty, dangerous, and costly.<br>
<br>
5) Proliferation promotion. Creates the largest source for U233 or Pu239. <br>
<br>
I consider these things nasties, not nicies. <br>
<br>
As the American Nuclear Society says:<br>
<br>
<br>
=======================================<br>
After listing some benefits of the FBR they continue:<br>
 <br>
&quot;There are some difficulties with the concept, however, that have prevented its widespread use.<br>
<br>
Sodium, the most commonly used metal, reacts explosively in air and water. <br>
Metals tend to solidify if not kept above a certain temperature; requiring complex maintenance procedures. <br>
Sodium becomes more radioactive than water when used as a coolant, again complicating routine maintenance. <br>
Metals cannot be used as working fluids, making a secondary cooling system a requirement. Normally, this is a steam system which causes some problems in design because of the sodium - water reaction possibility. <br>
There is an adequate supply of plutonium in the world for all current and projected needs; there is no market for any excess that can be produced in a reactor. <br>
<br>
Current Status<br>
Several LMFBRs have been built, with mixed results. Some of the difficulties associated with the plants are simply a result of the natural growing pains of any new technology. Other barriers, mostly related to the high price of the proposed systems when compared to alternative power sources, are more difficult to overcome. No commercially viable LMFBRs are currently in operation, but test programs proceed.&quot;<br>
